revision.text:
{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}} {{Use British English|date=February 2018}} The '''Abingdon Monks' Map''' (commonly known as '''The Monks' Map''') is a 16th-century map of the [[River Thames]] around the town of [[Abingdon, Oxfordshire]] (formerly in [[Berkshire]]), [[England]].<ref name="steane">{{cite journal | last=Steane | first=John | url=http://oxoniensia.org/volumes/2008/steane.pdf |title=The Abingdon Monks' Map | journal=[[Oxoniensia]] | publisher=[[Oxfordshire Architectural & Historical Society]] | volume=LXXII | pages=17–32 | year=2008 }}</ref> It is held in the collection of the [[Abingdon County Hall Museum]]. The map covers the stretch of river between Abingdon and [[Radley]]. It is {{convert|265.5|cm}} long and {{convert|41.5|cm}} wide, consisting of four pieces of [[vellum]] that are glued together.
==History== The map was preserved in the archives of the [[Verney family]], having been inherited by [[Mary Blacknall]] (1616–1650), who married [[Sir Ralph Verney, 1st Baronet, of Middle Claydon]] (1613–1696). In 1907, it was given to the Corporation of Abingdon and was framed and held in the Guildhall at Abingdon. The map was restored for a reopening of [[Abingdon Museum]], where it was put on display in 2012. As part of the investigation during this process, the map was x-rayed at the [[National Gallery]] in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehorsedc.gov.uk/services-and-advice/sports-and-leisure/libraries-and-museums/abingdon-abbey-booklet |title=Abingdon Abbey booklet |publisher=[[Vale of White Horse]] District Council, Oxfordshire, UK |accessdate=5 February 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120411184259/http://www.whitehorsedc.gov.uk/services-and-advice/sports-and-leisure/libraries-and-museums/abingdon-abbey-booklet |archivedate=11 April 2012 }}</ref>
==Monks map== {{Panorama |image = File:The Monks Map at Abingdon Museum.jpg |fullwidth = 4432 |fullheight = 689 |caption = Panoramic view of the Monks' Map, on display at [[Abingdon County Hall Museum]]. |height = 200 }}
==Blacknall Map== Another smaller map of the river, known as the '''Blacknall Map''' (or '''Claydon Map'''), is held at [[Claydon House]], the Verney family home, in [[Buckinghamshire]] to the north of Abingdon.<ref name="steane" /> This was produced for William Blacknall in support of his mill-owning and fishery rights during a lawsuit in 1570. The Monks' Map itself may well have been produced for a similar purpose rather than by monks at [[Abingdon Abbey]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-oxfordshire-13879363 | title=Monks' map was commissioned by Abingdon landowner | publisher=[[BBC News]] | work=Oxford | date=23 June 2011 | accessdate=5 February 2012}}</ref>
